WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.480 --> 00:00:04.560
Stretching from the eastern tips&nbsp;
of Oman over the Arabian Peninsula,

00:00:04.560 --> 00:00:10.800
across the Nile and along the northern edge of&nbsp;
the Sahara Desert, the Arab World has many facets,

00:00:10.800 --> 00:00:15.680
but none are quite as grand and awe-inspiring&nbsp;
as the towering mountains of the Maghreb,

00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:20.240
the western most region of the Arab World.
Several Mountain ranges stretch from Southern

00:00:20.240 --> 00:00:26.240
Morocco to the Tunisian Capital Tunis, which&nbsp;
are grouped under the term the Atlas Mountains.

00:00:26.240 --> 00:00:32.240
Across these 2300 kilometers, twice the&nbsp;
length of the alps, Northern Africa rises

00:00:32.240 --> 00:00:37.520
from the Sahara Desert before it plummets again&nbsp;
towards the Mediterranean Coast, covering many

00:00:37.520 --> 00:00:42.800
unique landscapes, climates and ecoregions.
In this video we will have a closer look into

00:00:42.800 --> 00:00:47.360
the constituting parts of this massive region,&nbsp;
starting our journey in southern Morocco,

00:00:47.360 --> 00:00:52.160
at the foothills of the Atlases oldest&nbsp;
mountains, the Anti-Atlas Mountain Range.

00:00:52.160 --> 00:00:56.720
As a disclaimer, some geographers exclude&nbsp;
these mountains from the greater Atlas Range

00:00:56.720 --> 00:01:00.080
due to its different origin story,&nbsp;
but for the sake of completeness,

00:01:00.080 --> 00:01:05.600
we will have a quick look at it anyways. The&nbsp;
Anti-Atlas, also known as the lesser Atlas,

00:01:05.600 --> 00:01:11.040
is significantly older than its northern&nbsp;
continuation. Around 250 million years ago, when

00:01:11.040 --> 00:01:17.040
the North America continental shelf was combined&nbsp;
with the African landmass as part of Pangea, the

00:01:17.040 --> 00:01:22.960
Alleghanian orogeny has formed a massive mountain&nbsp;
range along the intersection, creating what is today

00:01:22.960 --> 00:01:27.600
known as the Appalachians in North America and&nbsp;
the Atlas mountains of Morocco. The rest

00:01:27.600 --> 00:01:32.720
of the Atlas mountains are instead the product of&nbsp;
the African plate subducting under the Eurasian

00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:38.640
landmass starting around 66 million years ago,&nbsp;
putting it into a completely different category.

00:01:38.640 --> 00:01:42.880
Despite these different backstories, the&nbsp;
Anti-Atlas share many of the characteristics

00:01:42.880 --> 00:01:48.160
of the greater Atlas mountains. Surrounded&nbsp;
by the Draa River, Morocco's longest river

00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:53.760
at 1100 kilometers, these mountains have&nbsp;
a respectable size despite hundreds of millions

00:01:53.760 --> 00:01:59.360
of years of erosion, and the tallest peak, the&nbsp;
Djebel Siroua, which is visible from Marrakesh,

00:01:59.360 --> 00:02:05.760
stands at over 3300 meters above the sea level.&nbsp;
As a dormant volcano, it is the last identifiable

00:02:05.760 --> 00:02:10.480
volcanic remnant of the orogeny which has&nbsp;
stamped these mountains out of the ground.

00:02:10.480 --> 00:02:14.080
Standing in the rain shadow of the&nbsp;
taller High Atlas Mountains to the north,

00:02:14.080 --> 00:02:18.080
not much precipitation reaches this&nbsp;
region, and with an annual precipitation

00:02:18.080 --> 00:02:22.640
barely reaching 200 mm per year, it&nbsp;
is classified as a hot arid desert,

00:02:22.640 --> 00:02:25.920
together with the Sahara Desert&nbsp;
that it borders to the south.

00:02:25.920 --> 00:02:29.120
Separated by the Sous and&nbsp;
Dades rivers to the north,

00:02:29.120 --> 00:02:33.440
which have carved steep canyons into the&nbsp;
sandy rock, the tallest part of the Atlas

00:02:33.440 --> 00:02:38.560
mountains rises up on the other side of the&nbsp;
canyon walls, bringing us the High Atlas.

00:02:38.560 --> 00:02:44.000
Widely regarded as the heart of the Atlas range,&nbsp;
this section lies entirely within Morocco as well,

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:48.000
piercing through the country in a&nbsp;
south eastern, north western direction.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:53.760
Hundreds of parallel ridges are lining up across&nbsp;
its 100 km width, with the narrowest section in

00:02:53.760 --> 00:02:58.000
the middle, containing not just the highest peak&nbsp;
of Morocco, but also of The Atlas mountains,

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:06.000
the Maghreb region and North Africa as a whole.&nbsp;
At 4167 meters above sea level, this summit allows

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:11.280
for spectacular views onto the surrounding&nbsp;
ridges and the steppe in the far distance.

00:03:11.280 --> 00:03:14.640
This elevation makes the High Atlas 
the best winter sport destinations of

00:03:14.640 --> 00:03:21.120
Africa with Morocco's largest resort, Oukaïmeden,&nbsp;
receiving an average of 47 snow days in a winter,

00:03:21.120 --> 00:03:25.680
rivaling the best resorts of Europe. The snow&nbsp;
cover of the High Atlas is typically quite

00:03:25.680 --> 00:03:30.400
extensive, burying nearly the entire&nbsp;
length in a glimmering blanket every year.

00:03:30.400 --> 00:03:34.640
The barren landscape around the tallest&nbsp;
summits of the High Atlas are under strict

00:03:34.640 --> 00:03:39.120
protection today with a well developed national&nbsp;
park, attracting an ever increasing number of

00:03:39.120 --> 00:03:44.080
tourists into the country. Next to Hiking&nbsp;
and skiing, many of the tourists also flock in to

00:03:44.080 --> 00:03:49.440
enjoy the pristine star-gazing opportunities,&nbsp;
having turned Morocco into an astrophotography hot-spot

00:03:49.440 --> 00:03:50.703
in recent years.

00:03:50.720 --> 00:03:56.000
To quantify the clarity of the night sky, the&nbsp;
american amateur astronomer John Bortle has

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:01.600
devised the Bortle scale, which ranks a specific&nbsp;
location on earth by which celestial bodies are

00:04:01.600 --> 00:04:06.720
visible with the naked eye. The scale ranges&nbsp;
from inner-city skies where only the moon,

00:04:06.720 --> 00:04:11.360
planets and a few of the brightest star&nbsp;
clusters are visible, all the way to class 1,

00:04:11.360 --> 00:04:16.640
where globular clusters and otherwise faint&nbsp;
galaxies like the Triangulum Galaxy are clearly

00:04:16.640 --> 00:04:22.160
visible with the naked eye. These classifications are&nbsp;
largely based on peripheral light pollution

00:04:22.160 --> 00:04:27.120
from surrounding cities and villages but&nbsp;
as we move into more rural areas, nuances

00:04:27.120 --> 00:04:33.040
in the larger geography take over as the defining&nbsp;
factors. Mainly humidity and atmospheric particles

00:04:33.040 --> 00:04:38.400
are diminishing the view here, so a dry climate&nbsp;
and high elevation can improve the visibility.

00:04:38.400 --> 00:04:44.240
The High Atlas mountains excel in both aspects,&nbsp;
leading to a Bortle Scale class 1 and 2 throughout

00:04:44.240 --> 00:04:48.640
much of the region. While this isn’t the most&nbsp;
unique, with many very remote locations like

00:04:48.640 --> 00:04:53.680
the world's oceans also having class 1, the High&nbsp;
Atlas Mountains have the additional advantage that

00:04:53.680 --> 00:04:57.760
they are relatively easy accessible through&nbsp;
various hiking trails, and the proximity to

00:04:57.760 --> 00:05:02.800
the equator allows for the observation of both&nbsp;
northern and parts of the southern hemisphere.

00:05:02.800 --> 00:05:07.040
The north-south division, with one side&nbsp;
facing the mediterranean climate and the

00:05:07.040 --> 00:05:12.480
other facing the Saharan Desert further has a&nbsp;
strong impact on the ecoregion distribution,

00:05:12.480 --> 00:05:16.560
with the northern mountain faces receiving&nbsp;
significantly more precipitation than their

00:05:16.560 --> 00:05:22.320
Saharan counterparts. Ranging from 600 to&nbsp;
1000 millimeters per year, the northern faces

00:05:22.320 --> 00:05:27.280
can support light vegetation and some cedar and&nbsp;
oak trees, while the southern section is closer

00:05:27.280 --> 00:05:32.640
to a desert climate with precipitation&nbsp;
only ranging from 200-400 mm per year.

00:05:32.640 --> 00:05:37.760
Rising along this northern and more precipitous&nbsp;
slope, the Moulouya River, one of Morocco’s most

00:05:37.760 --> 00:05:42.560
important waterways for hydropower generation, is&nbsp;
separating the High Atlas from the Middle Atlas

00:05:42.560 --> 00:05:47.600
Mountains. The more mellow elevations and the&nbsp;
absence of a rain shadow make this region the most

00:05:47.600 --> 00:05:53.120
fertile stretch and the principal agricultural&nbsp;
region of the Moroccan Atlas. Especially apple

00:05:53.120 --> 00:05:58.608
trees, but also the cultivation of olives,&nbsp;
citrus fruits and sugar beets are widespread here.

00:05:58.640 --> 00:06:04.480
East of the Moroccan High and Middle Atlas, narrow&nbsp;
flat plains expand to the border with Algeria,

00:06:04.480 --> 00:06:08.320
from where two further sections of the&nbsp;
Atlas Mountains start to rise. Running

00:06:08.320 --> 00:06:11.520
parallel to the Mediterranean&nbsp;
Coast and the Saharan Desert,

00:06:11.520 --> 00:06:16.080
the Tell Atlas in the north and the Saharan&nbsp;
Atlas in the south stretch the full length

00:06:16.080 --> 00:06:20.880
of northern Algeria, with a massive bowl&nbsp;
occupying the lowlands in-between them.

00:06:20.880 --> 00:06:26.240
While the moist north, for North African standards&nbsp;
at least, houses most of the Algerian population,

00:06:26.240 --> 00:06:30.240
the Saharan Atlas is climatically very&nbsp;
similar to the name-giving desert of the

00:06:30.240 --> 00:06:35.280
south. Virtually no precipitation reaches&nbsp;
these areas, and the vegetation is barren,

00:06:35.280 --> 00:06:40.800
where only scattered palm trees and hardy&nbsp;
shrubs manage to survive in the sandy soils.

00:06:40.800 --> 00:06:44.160
This climate does not support&nbsp;
permanent waterways and instead,

00:06:44.160 --> 00:06:48.400
many of the rivers which drain the&nbsp;
Saharan Atlas are considered Wadi’s,

00:06:48.400 --> 00:06:53.520
a term used for temporary streams in the Arabic&nbsp;
Realm, which only appear during the wet-season.

00:06:53.520 --> 00:06:58.320
Flowing northwards, all streams from these&nbsp;
mountains eventually end in the Hautes Plaines,

00:06:58.320 --> 00:07:03.920
an elevated basin at 1300 meters in the&nbsp;
west, which gently slopes down to the east.

00:07:03.920 --> 00:07:09.120
The plain stretches over 600 kilometers between&nbsp;
the two mountain ranges and the steppe-like bowl

00:07:09.120 --> 00:07:13.360
is covered in deep alluvial debris from&nbsp;
the many rivers ending their course here.

00:07:13.360 --> 00:07:18.320
During the wet season, large but shallow lakes&nbsp;
form at the lowest parts of the bowl, but without

00:07:18.320 --> 00:07:23.680
any drainage to the sea, evaporation from the&nbsp;
intense sunlight quickly turns these into massive

00:07:23.680 --> 00:07:29.200
salt flats every year. The two major basins are&nbsp;
the Chott Ech Chergui in the center and the Chott

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:36.400
el Hodna in the east, with these flats&nbsp;
spanning a width of 160 and 77 km respectively.

00:07:36.400 --> 00:07:41.520
These basins stand in stark contrast to the&nbsp;
northerly Tell Atlas, which boast the wettest

00:07:41.520 --> 00:07:46.400
climate of Northern Africa, with some regions in&nbsp;
the east receiving as much as 1000 mm per

00:07:46.400 --> 00:07:51.920
year, which is twice the rainfall experienced&nbsp;
in London. The summers are however quite dry and

00:07:51.920 --> 00:07:56.720
long hot months still remind the people that&nbsp;
they are quite close to the Saharan Desert.

00:07:56.720 --> 00:08:01.280
To the east, both Atlas ranges gradually&nbsp;
merge into the Aures Mountains, which

00:08:01.280 --> 00:08:06.480
occupy the outermost section of the Atlas.&nbsp;
Straddling the Algerian-Tunisian border,

00:08:06.480 --> 00:08:09.520
these natural fortifications have&nbsp;
played an incredibly important

00:08:09.520 --> 00:08:14.160
part in Algeria's history all the way&nbsp;
from antiquity to the last century.

00:08:14.160 --> 00:08:19.040
The first described inhabitants that permanently&nbsp;
settled in the Atlas region are the Berbers,

00:08:19.040 --> 00:08:23.760
a group of people whose culture and identity&nbsp;
formed during the Pastoral Neolithic period,

00:08:23.760 --> 00:08:28.720
when the Sahara desert was still a&nbsp;
humid plain, around 10500 years ago.

00:08:28.720 --> 00:08:33.200
Throughout all of antiquity, these people had&nbsp;
to defend themselves against foreign forces,

00:08:33.200 --> 00:08:37.360
and the Aures mountains have been a major&nbsp;
retreat during invasions from the Romans,

00:08:37.360 --> 00:08:41.600
Byzantines, Vandals and Arabs that&nbsp;
spread along the North African Coast.

00:08:41.600 --> 00:08:45.840
Even in modern times, during the time of&nbsp;
the Algerian War for Independence from

00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:51.360
French occupiers between 1954 and 1962,&nbsp;
the Aures Mountains have presented the

00:08:51.360 --> 00:08:56.240
fortified base for the Algerian resistance&nbsp;
movement. Guerilla warfare tactics have been

00:08:56.240 --> 00:09:00.240
used in the hard to navigate terrain,&nbsp;
where local berbers had the upper hand,

00:09:00.240 --> 00:09:04.480
and the French colonial forces struggled&nbsp;
till the end of the war to control this area.

00:09:04.480 --> 00:09:09.520
Due to this inaccessibility, economic prospects&nbsp;
have been hard to pursue in recent decades, which

00:09:09.520 --> 00:09:15.200
is why the Aures Mountains are falling behind in&nbsp;
today's connected world. Across the Maghreb, it is

00:09:15.200 --> 00:09:20.880
the least developed region today, mostly relying&nbsp;
on subsistence agriculture and pastoralism.

00:09:20.880 --> 00:09:25.520
Surrounding this mountain range are the many Gulfs&nbsp;
of Tunesia’s coastline with several lakes and

00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:30.560
reservoirs occupying the valleys in the hinterland&nbsp;
of the coast. The largest of these is the Chott

00:09:30.560 --> 00:09:36.240
el Djerid in the south, which spans 200 by 75&nbsp;
kilometers and occupies a massive shallow

00:09:36.240 --> 00:09:41.600
basin. Similar to the lakes in the Hautes Plaines,&nbsp;
low precipitation in the summer bring this lake

00:09:41.600 --> 00:09:46.720
to near extinction every year, and its endorheic&nbsp;
geography, meaning that it has no outflows have

00:09:46.720 --> 00:09:52.800
turned it into a hypersaline environment. Lying 17&nbsp;
meters below the sea level, all the water draining

00:09:52.800 --> 00:09:57.760
from the Aures and Saharan Atlas is trapped just&nbsp;
a few kilometers before the Mediterranean Sea,

00:09:57.760 --> 00:10:02.400
and the salt and mineral deposits have&nbsp;
stained the landscape with vivid colors.

00:10:02.400 --> 00:10:05.742
Arriving on the easternmost end of 
the Atlas Mountains, we are concluding

00:10:05.742 --> 00:10:07.742
this journey through the incredible North African

00:10:07.760 --> 00:10:13.120
mountains. From the Prehistoric Anti-Atlas&nbsp;
over the snow covered giants of the High Atlas,

00:10:13.120 --> 00:10:17.760
along the Mediterranean Coast and Sahara&nbsp;
to the Algerian and Tunisian fortification,

00:10:17.760 --> 00:10:21.920
these mountains are a magnificent example&nbsp;
of mother nature's architectural abilities,

00:10:21.920 --> 00:10:27.200
and a reminder of how a little geographical&nbsp;
change can transform climates and landscapes.

00:10:27.200 --> 00:10:31.120
If you want to learn more about the most&nbsp;
incredible mountain ranges of this planet,

00:10:31.120 --> 00:10:35.760
you can check out these videos about the Rocky&nbsp;
Mountains or the Caucasus. And if you want to

00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:39.920
support the work I am doing on this channel even&nbsp;
more, you can now also leave a small donation on

00:10:39.920 --> 00:10:43.520
my Buy Me a Coffee page with the link in the&nbsp;
middle of the screen or in the description.

00:10:43.520 --> 00:10:49.000
See you in the next one, cheers!

